    <div class="QandA grid-item accented">
        <h4 class="Q">
            Q: How on Earth do you calculate all this stuff? <img class="faqarrow"
                src="https://www.flaticon.com/svg/static/icons/svg/892/892499.svg" height="1rem" width="1rem">
        </h4>
        <p class="A">A: Thankfully, clever people have already written formulae for working out how much energy
            a person burns. On JTMWTL, the Mifflin-St Jeor equation was adapted to find your TDEE. This is a more
            modern formula that has built on others that can before it. Nowadays, it is largely accepted to give
            the most accurate result. Calorie targets are simply a bit more or less than your TDEE.
        </p>
        <p class="A">Macros were calculated by taking the calorie target and calculating the daily protein, fats,
            and carbs in that order. Protein is 2.2g per kilo of body weight, fats are a certain percentage based
            on what you pick, and carbs fill the rest of the calories.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="QandA grid-item accented">
        <h4 class="Q">
            Q: What was each bit of the form for? <img class="faqarrow"
                src="https://www.flaticon.com/svg/static/icons/svg/892/892499.svg" height="1rem" width="1rem">
        </h4>
        <p class="A">A: Most are probably pretty obvious, but each question answered in the form was necessary for
            creating your personal plan. Height, weight, age and sex all affect TDEE and are used in the formula.
            Experience, goals and training frequency are needed to give a workout plan that you can actually stick
            to and will give you the results you're looking for. The carbohydrate question is just to tailor the
            nutrition slightly more to your tastes.
        </p>
        <p class="A">It's pretty simple, really. No need to answer more than you need to.
        </p>
    </div>
