    <div class="QandA grid-item accented">
        <h4 class="Q">
            Q: Why don't you offer 2 or 6 sessions a week? <img class="faqarrow"
                src="https://www.flaticon.com/svg/static/icons/svg/892/892499.svg" height="1rem" width="1rem">
        </h4>
        <p class="A">A: Part of it is to keep things simple and easy for the users. More choice isn't always better.
        </p>
        <p class="A">The other part of it is that 2 is probably too little and 6 is probably too much. People can make
            good progress on 2 sessions on a week, but the sessions would have to be pretty long and intense. 6 days
            can make for a great training schedule, but the returns you get over a 4 or 5 session a week plan is minimal.
            Or even non-existant. At that point, you're just training more because you like to train.
        </p>
        <p class="A">The vast majority of people should be training 3-5 days a week and enjoying other things on the other
            days.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="QandA bigQandA grid-item accented">
        <h4 class="Q">
            Q: What do 'beginner', 'novice' and 'intermediate' mean? <img class="faqarrow"
                src="https://www.flaticon.com/svg/static/icons/svg/892/892499.svg" height="1rem" width="1rem">
        </h4>
        <p class="A">A: Beginner is just that. Someone completely new to the gym and lifting weights. This person should
            be focusing on learning how to exercise properly.
        </p>
        <p class="A">Novice refers to someone that has been in the gym for a decent amount of time and seen some progress
            before, but still has a long way to go. A novice will still be able to make plenty of progress month to month.
        </p>
        <p class="A">To be an intermediate here, you will probably have done a lot of this before for probably well over a
            year. You've built strength that would impress most non-gym goers. You know all the exercises already. You can
            handle higher training volume and train consistently. You get a slightly more advanced plan, well done.
        </p>
        <p class="A">Why is there no expert? Well, that's because no expert lifter needs this site. These lifters have 
            trained intelligently for 5+ years and have dedicated a <i>lot</i> of time into it. The progress they make
            each year is minimal, as they are close to their genetic potential. Very few of us reach this point.
        </p>
    </div>